The [[Olympic closing ceremony|closing ceremony]] of the London [[2012 Summer Olympics]], also known as '''A Symphony of British Music''',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.ruvr.ru/2012_08_12/2012-Olympics-closing-ceremony-A-symphony-of-British-music/ |title=2012 Olympics closing ceremony: <U+2018>A symphony of British music<U+2019>|work=[[The Voice of Russia]] |date=12 August 2012 |accessdate=13 August 2012}}</ref> was held on 12 August in the [[Olympic Stadium (London)|Olympic Stadium]]. The event was created by [[Kim Gavin]], [[Es Devlin]], [[Stephen Daldry]], [[David Arnold]] and [[Mark Fisher (architect)|Mark Fisher]]. The worldwide broadcast began at 21:00 [[British Summer Time|BST]] ([[UTC+01:00|UTC+1]]) and finished at 00:11, lasting three hours and eleven minutes.  

The stadium had been turned into a giant representation of the Union Flag, designed by [[Damien Hirst]]. Around 4,100 people partook in the ceremony; which reportedly cost <U+00A3>20 million. The 2012 Summer Olympics were officially closed by [[Jacques Rogge]], who called London's games "happy and glorious." The ceremony included a handover to the next host city for the [[2016 Summer Olympics]], [[Rio de Janeiro]] and saw the Olympic flame extinguished and the flag lowered. The main part of the evening featured a one hour symphony of British Music as a number of British Pop acts appeared. Tributes to [[John Lennon]] and [[Freddie Mercury]] and the fashion industry were included in the section.  Rio marked the handover with an eight-minute section known as Embrace created by [[Cao Hamburger]] and [[Daniela Thomas]] featuring [[Pel<U+00E9>]]. [[Sebastian Coe]] gave a speech and the volunteers of London 2012 were thanked. 

An average of 23.2 million viewers in the United Kingdom watched the event, with an estimated 750 million worldwide. Critics were generally positive, but noted that it was not as good as the opening ceremony. Some of the foreign reviews questioned whether everyone would have understood the nods to British film and television. [[George Michael]] was roundly criticised for his song choice while [[Kate Moss]], [[Naomi Campbell]] and [[Russell Brand]] were criticised for not demonstrating the Olympic ethos in their past behaviour. [[Gary Barlow]] was praised for his appearance just a week after the death of his daughter. Some performers were initially reluctant to appear, other high profile acts refused to perform at the ceremony. [[NBC]] in America and [[Prime (New Zealand)|Prime TV]] in New Zealand were criticised by viewers for their broadcast of the ceremony. There was also a concert in [[Hyde Park, London|Hyde Park]] to close the Olympics, headlined by [[Blur (band)|Blur]].

{{2012 Summer Olympics}}

==Production==
The creative director and choreographer was [[Kim Gavin]],<ref name=bbc>{{cite web|title=Profile: Kim Gavin, director of Olympic closing ceremony|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-19094398|work=[[BBC News]]|date=10 August 2012|accessdate=11 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=telegraph>{{cite news|title=Kim Gavin: profile of Cultural Olympiad ceremony director|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/cultural-olympiad/8332914/Kim-Gavin-profile-of-Cultural-Olympiad-ceremony-director.html|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|location=London|date=18 February 2011|accessdate=11 August 2012}}</ref> with [[Es Devlin]] responsible for design and [[David Arnold]] as musical director.<ref>{{citenews|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2011/feb/18/kim-gavin-london-2012-closing-ceremonies|title=Kim Gavin named artistic director for London 2012 closing ceremonies|first=Amelia|last=Hill|date=18 February 2011|accessdate=24 February 2013|work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref> When Arnold was announced in his role he said that doing the closing ceremony was an honour and a once in a lifetime opportunity.<ref>{{citenews|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/cultural-olympiad/8332882/James-Bond-composer-David-Arnold-will-be-2012-musical-director.html|title=Bond composer will be 2012 musical director|date=18 February 2011|accessdate=1 March 2013|work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> While Gavin stated that he was really excited and honoured to be involved. Davlin said that she was delighted to be part of the greatest show on earth. [[Hugh Robertson (politician)|Hugh Robertson]], [[Minister for Sport and the Olympics]], stated that he was delighted to have a high quality team working on the ceremony. While [[Boris Johnson]] stated that we have the best of British creating the bookends to our Games.<ref>{{citenews|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/cultural-olympiad/8332853/Top-British-talent-will-direct-closing-ceremonies-of-London-Olympics.html|title=Top British talent will direct closing ceremonies of London Olympics|first=Martin|last=Chilton|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=18 February 2011|accessdate=1 March 2013}}</ref> [[Stephen Daldry]] was the executive producer and [[Mark Fisher (architect)|Mark Fisher]] was in charge of production design. The ceremony cost <U+00A3>20 million, with the artists paid just <U+00A3>1 for contractual purposes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/9469312/Olympics-closing-ceremony-spectacular-end-to-the-Games-will-celebrate-50-years-of-British-pop.html |title=Olympics closing ceremony: spectacular end to the Games will celebrate 50 years of British pop |work=The Daily Telegraph |first1=Patrick|last1=Sawar|first2=Claire|last2=Duffin |date=12 August 2012 |accessdate=30 August 2012}}</ref> Around 4,100 performers took part, comprising 3,500 adult volunteers, 380 schoolchildren from the six original host boroughs, and 250 professionals. There had been around 15 rehearsals for the volunteers at the [[Three Mills|Three Mills Studio]] and at a full scale site in [[Dagenham]], East London.<ref name="telegraph">{{cite web|author=Cultural Olympiad |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/cultural-olympiad/9101768/Adele-and-Elgar-mash-up-to-close-Olympic-Games.html |title=Adele and Elgar 'mash-up' to close Olympic Games |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=23 Feburay 2012 |accessdate=29 June 2012}}</ref>

Gavin said that <U+201C>the show we are putting on is very shiny, it's very colourful. We don't want to bang on about our culture. We just want to have fun.<U+201D>  Es Devlin added that it "has to make sense in [[Bognor Regis|Bognor]] and [[Bogot<U+00E1>]]."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/news/9469271/Olympics-closing-ceremony-weve-had-the-wedding-now-its-time-for-the-disco.html |title=Olympics closing ceremony: we<U+2019>ve had the wedding, now it<U+2019>s time for the disco |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=30 August 2012|first=Cole|last=Moreton|date=11 August 2012}}</ref> She said that the creators had happily indulged in the chance to "visually draw on everything" that British imagination can offer.<ref name="telegraph"/> David Arnold said <U+201C>It's going to be beautiful, cheeky, cheesy, camp, silly and thrilling",<ref name="telegraph2">{{cite web|title=London 2012 Closing Ceremony: here come the Spice Girls|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/news/9466698/London-2012-Closing-Ceremony-here-come-the-Spice-Girls.html|first=Anita|last=Singh|date=10 August 2012|accessdate=30 August 2012|work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> and added that "we could have done this 15 times over, and not had the same show, and it would still have been full of amazing British music". He thought that it should be the "greatest after party" and was <U+201C>really a celebration of Britishness in terms of [all] the arts". Arnold himself had devoted two years working on the ceremony and had turned down all other work including ''[[Skyfall]]'', but said that it was the "most fun" he had "ever had in music".<ref>{{cite web|author=Rock and Pop Features |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopfeatures/9462324/Olympics-Closing-Ceremony-Its-going-to-be-cheeky-cheesy-and-thrilling.html|first=Neil|last=McCormick |title=Olympics Closing Ceremony: 'It<U+2019>s going to be cheeky, cheesy and thrilling<U+2019> |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=9 August 2012 |accessdate=30 August 2012}}</ref> In the handover section Rio aimed to express "multicultural embrace." [[Daniela Thomas]] stated that Rio "want to show you how sophisticated we mix things, what we do with the things you believe we are, how we mix with pop culture."<ref>{{cite news|last=Reynolds|first=Tim|title=Rio getting ready for its Olympic turn|url=http://sports.yahoo.com/news/rio-getting-ready-olympic-turn-145521014--oly.html|publisher=Yahoo Sports|agency=Associated Press|date=10 August 2012|accessdate=1 March 2013}}</ref>

The representation of the [[Union Flag]] used as an arena centrepiece was designed by [[Damien Hirst]] to celebrate the "anarchy and diversity of British pop art, and by extension the energy and multiplicity of contemporary British culture". Hirst had been approached in November 2011 and agreed to do the design; he called his artwork ''Beautiful Union Jack Celebratory Patriotic Olympic Explosion in an Electric Storm Painting''. 176 photographs made up one centimetre of the stadium artwork with graphic designers having spent three months creating super-high-resolution images before printing.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/london-2012/9484348/London-2012-Olympics-why-we-reinvented-the-Union-flag-for-the-Closing-Ceremony.html|title=Why we reinvented the Union flag for the Closing Ceremony|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=19 August 2012|accessdate=26 August 2012|first=Es|last=Devlin}}</ref> 

Some performers had declined to perform, including [[The Rolling Stones]], [[David Bowie]], [[Sex Pistols]], [[Kate Bush]] and [[The Libertines]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The Rolling Stones, David Bowie, Sex Pistols, Kate Bush and The Libertines turned down Olympic closing ceremony|url=http://www.nme.com/news/david-bowie/65495|work=[[NME]]|date=13 August 2012|accessdate=16 August 2012}}</ref><ref name="Bowie"/> According to industry insiders The Who apparently refused twice, and only agreed once they had announced a US tour. The [[Spice Girls]] were said to be reluctant to appear, feeling that the event was being staged at minimal cost, before their manager [[Simon Fuller]] persuaded them to perform.<ref name="Bowie">{{cite web|first=Dan |last=Sabbagh |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2012/aug/13/david-bowie-olympics-closing-ceremony |title=David Bowie among UK stars who turned down Olympic closing show |work=The Guardian |date=13 August 2012 |accessdate=30 August 2012}}</ref> [[Noel Gallagher]] turned down the chance to perform after first being asked to play acoustically and then to mime to "[[Wonderwall (song)|Wonderwall]]".<ref>{{cite news|title=Noel Gallagher turned down Olympic closing ceremony|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-19281176|work=[[BBC News]]|date=16 August 2012|accessdate=16 August 2012|work=BBC News}}</ref>

[[Elizabeth II|The Queen]] and the [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|Duke of Edinburgh]] were not scheduled to attend as there is no formal role for the Head of State during the ceremony. The royal family was represented by [[Prince Harry of Wales|Prince Harry]], [[Anne, Princess Royal|the Princess Royal]] and [[Catherine, Duchess of Cambridge|the Duchess of Cambridge]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/queen-elizabeth-II/9470902/Olympics-closing-ceremony-Queen-praises-athletes-but-will-not-be-there.html |title=Olympics closing ceremony: Queen praises athletes but will not be there |work=The Daily Telegraph |date= |accessdate=30 August 2012|first=Gordon|last=Rayner|12 August 2012}}</ref>

==Performance synopsis==

===Rush Hour (21:00<U+2013>21:09)===
[[File:Miniature London at 2012 Olympic Closing Ceremony.jpg|thumb|left|250px|Landmarks in the stadium.]]
The ceremony began after a filmed countdown showing numbers from around London on such locations as road signs, [[10 Downing Street]] and the [[Palace of Westminster]] clock tower, with a camera panning up the [[River Thames]] over [[Tower Bridge]] before turning left towards the stadium.  The audience then completed a 10-second countdown to the start of the ceremony, to the chimes of [[Big Ben]].  The arena had been transformed into a huge representation of the [[Union Flag]] in black and white,<ref name="Yemanja"/> with ramps and famous London landmarks such as the [[London Eye]], Big Ben, [[Battersea Power Station]] and the [[30 St Mary Axe|Gherkin]]. Newspaper cutouts on both the set and road vehicles sought to show a "day in the life of London", with words from British literary figures such as [[William Shakespeare]], [[J. R. R. Tolkien]] and [[Poet Laureate of the United Kingdom|Poet Laureate]] [[Carol Ann Duffy]].<ref name="Del Boy"/>

[[Emeli Sand<U+00E9>]] appeared on a truck and sang a verse and the chorus of "[[Read All About It (song)|Read All About It (Pt III)]]". The Urban Voices Collective (the choir for the ceremony) sang [[The Beatles|The Beatles']] "[[Because (The Beatles song)|Because]]", which merged into cellist [[Julian Lloyd Webber]] (sat upon the [[Royal Albert Hall]]<ref name="Yemanja"/>) playing [[Elgar]]'s [[Salut d'amour]], accompanied by [[Stomp (dance troupe)|Stomp]] performing on household items such as pots, pans and dustbins while suspended on the sculptures of the landmarks.

===God Save the Queen===
At the same time, [[Winston Churchill]] ([[Timothy Spall]]) appeared at the top of [[Elizabeth Tower|Big Ben]] and reprised Caliban's "Be not afeard" speech from ''[[The Tempest]]'', first read by [[Kenneth Branagh]] in the [[2012 Summer Olympics opening ceremony|opening ceremony]]. More paper-covered motor vehicles entered. After Churchill finished his speech, people dressed in newspaper print began to fill the arena, ranging from office workers to school children. The beat of the music got faster and noisier, symbolising the London rush hour.  As the noise reached a crescendo, Churchill cried out for all to stop, bringing this section to an end.

[[Prince Henry of Wales]], representing the Queen, arrived with the President of the [[International Olympic Committee]] [[Jacques Rogge]]. The [[London Symphony Orchestra]] and the Urban Voice Choir performed the [[God Save the Queen|national anthem of the United Kingdom]] whilst the Union flag was raised by the armed forces and the performers waved mini Union flags in the stadium. Once the flag was raised Hirst's artwork was revealed as the grey clouds were removed.<ref name="Yemanja"/>

===Street Party (21:09<U+2013>21:20)===
This section started off with [[Michael Caine]] counting down from five, whereupon the [[Reliant Regal]] from ''[[Only Fools and Horses]]'' exploded with Del Boy and Rodney jumping out dressed as [[Batman]] and Robin.  Caine's words, ''[[The Italian Job|You were only supposed to blow the bloody doors off!]]'', echoed around the stadium. All the lorries had the newspaper removed and a colourful street party erupted, while [[Madness (band)|Madness]] performed "[[Our House (Madness song)|Our House]]". This was followed by the Massed Bands of the [[Household Division]] marching whilst playing [[Blur (band)|Blur]]'s "[[Parklife (song)|Parklife]]". Entering on [[cycle rickshaw|rickshaws]], the [[Pet Shop Boys]] performed their hit "[[West End Girls]]", and then [[One Direction]] performed "[[What Makes You Beautiful]]" from the back of a lorry. Next there was another performance by Stomp.

===Waterloo Sunset (21:20<U+2013>21:30)===
The centre of the arena was then cleared to reveal ''[[Britain's Got Talent]]'' 2010 winners [[Spelbound]], who performed gymnastics to [[The Beatles]] "[[A Day in the Life]]", were inspired by the idea of a commuter on the way to work, by forming a bed and a London Bus. [[Ray Davies]] of [[The Kinks]] arrived in a [[Hackney carriage|black cab]] and played "[[Waterloo Sunset]]", as Spelbound continued and local school children formed the themes.  The section closed with Sand<U+00E9> reprising "Read All About It (Pt. III)" as a montage of athletes crying in victory or defeat was shown on the screens.

===Parade of Athletes (21:30<U+2013>21:53)===
[[File:Athletes at the 2012 Closing Ceremony.jpg|thumb|Olympic athletes assembled in the shape of the [[Union Flag]]]]
[[Greece at the 2012 Summer Olympics|Greece]] led the Entrance of the Flags, as all 204 flags filed in to the strains of "Parade of the Athletes" (composed by Arnold) and marched up the central cross of the union flag, with [[Great Britain at the 2012 Summer Olympics|Great Britain]] bringing up the rear. Meanwhile, volunteer marshals wearing blue suits and blue bowler hats with light bulbs on top marched into the stadium. The athletes then walked in from the several entrances, with some filtering down through the lower stands. As the same time [[Elbow (band)|Elbow]] performed "[[Open Arms (Elbow song)|Open Arms]]" and "[[One Day Like This]]". The volunteer marshals helped to usher the athletes into pens between the ramps of the arena. As the last athletes streamed into the stadium and the flags were moved by volunteers closer to the Olympic Flame, a reprise of some of the songs from the opening section was played.

===Here Comes the Sun (21:53<U+2013>22:07)===
{{main|2012 Summer Olympics closing ceremony flag bearers}}
16 [[dhol]] drummers opened this segment as the performers entered carrying 303 white boxes to symbolise every event in the Olympic Games. The drumming merged into [[Kate Bush]]'s "[[Running Up that Hill|Running Up That Hill (A Deal With God Remix)]]", as performers arranged the boxes to form a pyramid while video highlights from the previous 16 days of competition were shown on the screens. 

This was followed by the victory ceremony for the [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Olympics <U+2013> Men's marathon|Men's Marathon]], by tradition the final medal ceremony of the Games. Rogge and [[Lamine Diack]], president of the [[International Association of Athletics Federations]], awarded the medals before the [[Oh Uganda, Land of Beauty|Ugandan national anthem]] was played. 

Six athletes including [[Katherine Grainger]] and [[Katie Taylor]] presented flowers to six volunteers in a symbolic recognition of the 70,000 volunteers' contribution to the Games.  This part of the ceremony was accompanied by The Beatles' "[[Here Comes the Sun]]".

===A Symphony of British Music (22:07<U+2013>23:21)===
[[File:John Lennon face sculpture, 2012 London Olympics closing ceremony.jpg|thumb|A sculpture of the face of [[John Lennon]] at the closing ceremony.]]
The section commenced with Queen's "[[Bohemian Rhapsody]]" being played and a graphic equaliser being shown on the pixel screen.  [[John Lennon]] then appeared on the big screens and was joined by Choirs of Liverpool in singing "[[Imagine (song)|Imagine]]" as a bust of Lennon's face was created. Balloons were released at the end of this and [[George Michael]] followed singing "[[Freedom! '90]]" and "[[White Light (George Michael song)|White Light]]". A group of [[Mod (subculture)|mods]] on [[Scooter (motorcycle)|scooters]] followed invading the arena; one of them carried [[Ricky Wilson (British musician)|Ricky Wilson]] to the stage where his band the [[Kaiser Chiefs]] proceeded to cover [[The Who|The Who's]] "[[Pinball Wizard]]"; during the song the scooters continued to circle the arena. Several extracts of [[David Bowie]] songs followed, accompanied by images of Bowie; this continued until eight billboards with artwork of models on arrived in the stadium, representing the British fashion industry. The artwork was dropped to reveal the models standing behind: [[Naomi Campbell]] (wearing [[Alexander McQueen (brand)|Alexander McQueen]]),<ref name="Fashion">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/london-2012/9471522/London-2012-Team-of-role-models-made-this-the-Girl-Power-Games.html|first=Bryony|last=Gordon|date=13 August 2012|accessdate=20 August 2012|work=The Daily Telegraph|title=Team of role models made this the Girl Power Games}}</ref><ref name="Fashion 2">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/9471476/London-2012-closing-ceremony-Fashion-superstars-show-why-Britain-is-catwalk-gold.html|title=Fashion superstars show why Britain is catwalk gold|first=Luke|last=Leitch|date=13 August 2012|accessdate 20 August 2012|work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> [[Lily Cole]] (wearing [[Erdem]]),<ref name="Fashion 2"/> [[Karen Elson]] (wearing [[Burberry]]),<ref name="Fashion 2"/> [[Lily Donaldson]] (wearing [[Vivienne Westwood]]),<ref name="Fashion"/><ref name="Fashion 2"/> [[Jourdan Dunn]] (wearing [[Jonathan Saunders]]),<ref name="Fashion"/><ref name="Fashion 2"/> [[David Gandy]] (wearing [[Paul Smith (fashion designer)|Paul Smith]]),<ref name="Fashion 2"/> [[Georgia May Jagger]] (wearing [[Victoria Beckham#Fashion|Victoria Beckham]]),<ref name="Fashion"/><ref name="Fashion 2"/> [[Kate Moss]] (wearing [[Alexander McQueen (brand)|Alexander McQueen]])<ref name="Fashion"/><ref name="Fashion 2"/> and [[Stella Tennant]] (wearing [[Christopher Kane]]).<ref name="Fashion"/><ref name="Fashion 2"/>  The models concluded the section by turning the struts of the [[Union Flag]] into a [[catwalk]] as they proceeded to the centre, walking to Bowie's 1980 single "[[Fashion (David Bowie song)|Fashion]]".

A wooden boat was then carried in; on board was [[Annie Lennox]] who proceeded to sing "[[Little Bird (Annie Lennox song)|Little Bird]]". [[Ed Sheeran]] followed and was joined by [[Richard Jones (bassist)|Richard Jones]] of [[The Feeling]], [[Nick Mason]] of [[Pink Floyd]] and [[Mike Rutherford]] of [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]] and [[Mike + The Mechanics]], to cover the Floyd's "[[Wish You Were Here (Pink Floyd song)|Wish You Were Here]]". Near the end of the song a performer appeared on a tightrope above the stadium, walked along it, and shook hands with a mannequin, which then burst into flames (referencing the cover of Floyd's 1975 album ''[[Wish You Were Here (Pink Floyd album)|Wish You Were Here]]''). A bus then entered with [[Russell Brand]] sitting on top of it miming "[[I Am the Walrus]];" before introducing [[Fatboy Slim]], who played "[[Right Here, Right Now (Fatboy Slim song)|Right Here Right Now]]" and "[[The Rockafeller Skank]]"; as the bus slowly transformed into a large inflatable Octopus. Three convertible [[Rolls-Royce Phantom Drophead Coup<U+00E9>]]s then arrived; the roof of the first was taken down to reveal [[Jessie J]] who sang her hit "[[Price Tag]]", as the cars did a lap of the stadium. Jessie J provided guest vocals as the next car had its roof removed, to show [[Tinie Tempah]] who sang "[[Written in the Stars (Tinie Tempah song)|Written in the Stars]]". The third car carried [[Taio Cruz]] who sang "[[Dynamite (Taio Cruz song)|Dynamite]]". All three then left the cars to combine to cover the [[Bee Gees]]' "[[You Should Be Dancing]]".

[[File:London cabs with Spice Girls.jpg|thumb|left|Cabs carrying the [[Spice Girls]].]]
A number of black cabs entered the stadium, five of which lit up with LED lights, each decorated with [[The Spice Girls]]' individual trademark embalms, (Posh: sparkling black, Sporty: go-faster stripes, Scary: leopard print, Baby: pink and Ginger: The Union Flag). The Spice Girls emerged from the cabs and performed "[[Wannabe (song)|Wannabe]]" and "[[Spice Up Your Life]]". Half way through their performance, they ascended onto the roofs of the cabs and proceeded to race around the stadium at seemingly fast speeds whilst singing and dancing from the roofs. 
[[Beady Eye]] followed by performing [[Oasis (band)|Oasis's]] "[[Wonderwall (song)|Wonderwall]]". "[[Mr. Blue Sky]]" by [[Electric Light Orchestra]] was played as a tribute to aviation was performed. Near the end of this song a human cannonball "died" and out rolled [[Eric Idle]], who sang "[[Always Look on the Bright Side of Life]]", accompanied variously by nuns on roller-skates, [[Morris dance]]rs (Blackheath Morris and Rag Morris),<ref name="volunteers">{{cite web|url=http://www.london2012.com/mm/Document/Documents/General/01/39/69/96/OCCVolunteers_Neutral.pdf |title=Volunteers B<U+00E9>n<U+00E9>voles |work=London Organising Committee of the Olympic Games and Paralympic Games |accessdate=10 September 2012|format=PDF}}</ref> Roman soldiers,<ref name="aljaz"/> and Punjabi [[Bhangra (music)|bhangra musicians]] [[Bhangra (dance)|dancers]] (VP Bhangra),<ref name="volunteers"/> before a [[human cannonball]] was fired across the arena.<ref name="aljaz">ref name="aljaz">{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/europe/2012/08/201281305330562117.html |title=London ends Olympics on extravagant notes <U+2013> Europe |work=Al Jazeera English |date=4 October 2011 |accessdate=13 August 2012}}</ref> [[Muse (band)|Muse]] then appeared and proceeded to sing the official song of London 2012, "[[Survival (Muse song)|Survival]]".<ref name="London2012Rio2016"/> In the darkness four trucks with screens on them entered and went to the centre of the stadium. [[Freddie Mercury]] then appeared on these and other screens around the stadium, before his bandmate [[Brian May]] performed a guitar solo. May was then joined by [[Roger Meddows Taylor|Roger Taylor]] to re-form Queen, as Jessie J, who wore a long yellow jacket in homage to Mercury accompanied the pair for "[[We Will Rock You]]."  More fireworks ended this section.

===The Road to Rio (23:21<U+2013>23:30)===
The section began with the [[Hymn to Liberty|Greek national anthem]] being played and raising of the flag; followed by the [[Olympic anthem]] and the lowering of the flag.  [[The Mayor of London]], [[Boris Johnson]], then handed the Olympic Flag to [[Jacques Rogge]], who in turn passed it to [[Eduardo Paes]], [[mayor of Rio de Janeiro|the Mayor of Rio de Janeiro]].<ref name="aljaz"/> This was followed by the [[Hino Nacional Brasileiro|Brazilian national anthem]] and raising of the flag. The Olympic Flag will be raised again in [[Sochi]] on 7 February 2014 at the opening ceremony of the [[2014 Winter Olympics]].

===Embrace (23:30<U+2013>23:38)===
[[File:Rio takeover.jpg|thumb|right|The end of Rio's segment.]]
Rio then provided an eight-minute segment to introduce the world to its city, created by [[Cao Hamburger]] and [[Daniela Thomas]] entitled "Embrace".<ref name="London2012Rio2016"/> The showcase presented both indigenous and Latin culture, as well as some mock [[Rio Carnival]] performers, and began with the street cleaner Renato Sorriso dancing [[samba]] joined by sailor [[Robert Scheidt]]. The section continued with a Carnival-eqsue Samba parade as various artists performed, including singers [[Marisa Monte]] (dressed as water goddess [[Yemanja]]<ref name="Yemanja">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2187413/London-2012-Closing-Ceremony-Eric-Idle-leads-crowd-rendition-Always-Look-Bright-Side-Life.html|title=Feeling sad about the end of the Games? Eric Idle leads 80,000 crowd in rendition of Always Look on the Bright Side of Life|date=13 August 2012|accessdate24 August 2012|first=Ian|last=Garland|work=[[The Daily Mail]]}}</ref>), [[:pt:BNeg<U+00E3>o|BNeg<U+00E3>o]] and [[Seu Jorge]], with an appearance by model [[Alessandra Ambrosio]]. [[Jorge Mautner]] and [[Heitor Villa-Lobos]] both received tributes.  It concluded with an appearance by [[Pel<U+00E9>]], who was wearing a Brazilian football shirt with his name and the number 10 on the back and a 3D model of Rio's logo. Brazil's section finished with a fireworks display.

===Closing of the Games (23:38<U+2013>23:48)===
[[File:Cauldron and Phoneix at the 2012 Olympic Closing Ceremony.jpg|right|thumb|upright|Opening of the Olympic cauldron.]]
[[Sebastian Coe]] and [[Jacques Rogge]] then appeared on a stage that was in the form of an arrow pointing towards Rio.<ref name="Del Boy">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/london-2012/9471474/London-2012-Closing-Ceremony-Del-Boy-and-Darcey-give-Rio-a-unique-act-to-follow.html|title=Del Boy and Darcey give Rio a unique act to follow|date=13 August 2012|accessdate=20 August 2012|first=Gordon|last=Rayner|work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> Coe thanked all of the people who had helped make the Olympics happen. He said that the volunteers, who received another huge cheer, had the right to say "I made London, 2012". Coe thanked the country for getting behind the Games, and recalled his words from the Opening Ceremony "these will be a games for everyone", concluding "these were a games ''by'' everyone." He went on to thank the athletes and say that "the spirit of these Olympics will inspire a generation", before concluding that "when our time came, Britain, we did it right!".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/london-2012/9471489/London-2012-We-lit-up-the-world-says-Lord-Coe.html|title='We lit up the world' says Lord Coe|first=Hannah|last=Furness|date=13 August 2012|accessdate=20 August 2012|work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref>

Rogge thanked Coe and his [[London Organising Committee of the Olympic and Paralympic Games]] team, saying that they had done a "superb job". He said "we are indebted to so many tonight", thanking the "wonderful volunteers, the much needed heroes of these Games", as well as the British public and the athletes. Rogge said that the athletes had earned the right to be called 'Olympians' due to the fair play and graciousness that they had shown, and he looked forward to the [[2012 Summer Paralympics|Paralympic Games]]. Rogge concluded by calling the Games "happy and glorious", before proceeding to close the competition and calling upon the youth of the world to assemble in [[2016 Summer Olympic Games|Rio in 2016]], ending with "Thank you, London!".<ref>{{cite news|url=
http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/london-2012/9471505/London-2012-Jacques-Rogge-praises-happy-and-glorious-games.html|first1=Gordon|last1=Rayner|first2=Sam|last2=Marsden|title=Jacques Rogge praises 'happy and glorious' games|date=13 August 2012|accessdate=20 August 2012|work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.olympic.org/Documents/Games_London_2012/London_2012_Closing_Ceremony_English.pdf|title=London 2012 Closing Ceremony|format=PDF|work=International Olympic Committee}}</ref>

===Spirit of the Flame (23:48<U+2013>00:00)===
{{See also|2012 Summer Olympics and Paralympics cauldron}}
The arms holding the copper petals that formed the [[2012 Summer Olympics and Paralympics cauldron|Olympic cauldron]] were part-lowered, and fireworks set off behind; when the smoke had cleared, a [[Phoenix (mythology)|phoenix]] was seen above the flames. [[Take That]] then performed "[[Rule the World]]". [[Darcey Bussell]] followed flying down from the top of the stadium in a guise of a phoenix and was joined by four male principle dancers from the [[The Royal Ballet]], [[Gary Avis]], [[Jonathan Cope (dancer)|Jonathan Cope]], [[Nehemiah Kish]] and [[Edward Watson (dancer)|Ed Watson]] and over 200 ballerinas,<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://olympicclosingceremony.tumblr.com/tagged/stage10|title=Spirit of the flame|work=London 2012}}</ref><ref name="London2012Rio2016">{{citenews|url=http://www.london2012.com/media-centre/article=london-throws-world-biggest-party-for-olympic-athletes-closing-ceremony-spectacular.html|title=London throws World biggest party of Olympic athletes closing ceremony spectacular|work=London 2012|date=12 August 2012}}</ref> who proceeded to perform a dance called 'the spirit of the flame', after which the [[Olympic Flame]] was extinguished.

===Finale (00:00<U+2013>00:07)===
The closing act of the ceremony was [[The Who]], who performed a medley of the songs "[[Baba O'Riley]]", "[[See Me, Feel Me]]" and "[[My Generation]]" as a montage of images of Games volunteers and Londoners appeared on the big screen. All star performers also appeared on the stage behind the band, while participants in the ceremony also marched through the centrestage towards The Who. The set concluded to massive fireworks set off in the stadium and around the Olympic Park.

==Technical aspects==
[[File:Pixels London 2012.jpg|thumb|right|One of the images created with the pixels during the ceremony]] 634,500 individual LED pixels were used to create 27 images lasting 75 minutes. The pixels were created by Crystal CG and each animation was constructed by a team of six, whilst a team of eight created the Rio segment. Images including catwalk models in high-end fashions, drifting clouds over London and flicking paint onto rooftop canvases were shot for the effects.<ref>{{cite web|first=Anthony |last=Bond |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2187468/The-greatest-disco-Earth-Pixel-animations-turn-Olympic-Stadium-psychedelic-light-show.html |title=The greatest disco on Earth! Pixel animations turn Olympic Stadium into psychedelic light show |work=The Daily Mail |date=13 August 2012 |accessdate=30 August 2012}}</ref>

The broadcast of the Olympic closing ceremony featured [[1080p]] and side-by-side [[1080i]] [[3D television|3D]] on various TV channels and online.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01m315q BBC TV and HD channel listing]</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/news/2012-02-16/bbc-to-broadcast-london-2012-olympics-ceremonies-and-100m-final-in-3d|title=BBC to broadcast London 2012 Olympics ceremonies and 100m final in 3D|first=Paul|last=Jones|publisher=[[Radio Times]]|date=16 February 2012|accessdate=1 March 2013}}</ref>

==Ratings and reviews==
An estimated worldwide television audience of 750 million watched the event.<ref name="aljaz">{{cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/europe/2012/08/201281305330562117.html |title=London ends Olympics on extravagant notes <U+2013> Europe |publisher=Al Jazeera English |date=4 October 2011 |accessdate=2012-08-13}}</ref> Early data suggested that the British TV audience averaged 23.2 million and hit a peak of 26.2 million at 21:35.<ref name="Bowie"/><ref name="GB viewing"/>

The ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'' commented during the ceremony that, although fun, it lacked "top drawer" performers, and that Annie Lennox was "utterly underwhelming."  However One Direction, Jessie J, Tinie Tempah and Taio Cruz "shone", while the Spice Girls "got the exuberant tone exactly right".<ref>{{cite web|first=Bernadette|last= McNulty|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopreviews/9467519/Olympic-Closing-Ceremony-London-2012-review.html |title=Olympic Closing Ceremony London 2012: review |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=12 August 2012 |accessdate=13 August 2012}}</ref> Tom Sutcliffe writing for ''[[The Independent]]'' said that it was "slick, impressive, often visually startling" and "eccentric, bewildering <U+2013> and shameless good fun". He added that "where Danny Boyle's opening show had been a statement of intent and national values, this was an hour-long advert for British stadium rock-show design."<ref>{{cite news|last=Sutcliffe|first=Tom|title=London Olympics 2012 closing ceremony: Eccentric, bewildering <U+2013> and shameless good fun|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/reviews/london-olympics-2012-closing-ceremony-eccentric-bewildering--and-shameless-good-fun-8037281.html|work=[[The Independent]]|date=13 August 2012|accessdate=11 March 2013}}</ref>

[[The Guardian]] writer [[Michael Billington (critic)|Michael Billington]] wrote that he was not sure how to review "a mix of pageant, pop-concert, street-party and presentation ceremony." He added that it communicated the "energy of British popular culture over the past few decades and the gaiety of our Olympic ceremonies."  Billington praised Boyle, Devlin and Daldry, who had done a "tremendous job in lending what might have been orthodox Olympic rituals a blast of theatrical vitality."<ref>{{cite web|first=Michael|last=Billington |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2012/aug/13/london-2012-olympic-games-closing-ceremony-review?INTCMP=SRCH |title=London 2012 closing ceremony - review |work=The Guardian |date=13 August 2012 |accessdate=30 August 2012}}</ref> While Alexis Petridis writing for the same paper said that the lack of a "gasp inducing moment" spoilt the show.<ref>{{cite web|first=Alexis|last= Petridis |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2012/aug/13/olympics-closing-ceremony-music-review?intcmp=239 |title=Olympics closing ceremony music: big acts, big hits, but no big gasps |work=The Guardian |date=13 August 2012 |accessdate=30 August 2012}}</ref> [[Jan Moir]] of the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' queried whether the ceremony truly reflected Britain's musical heritage and described the opening section as "dull, dull, dull".  She asked "how could anyone follow the Opening Ceremony for entertainment?", challenged "the logic" of clips of artists such as Bush and Bowie who had "declined to appear", and said that the fashion section was "dreary".<ref>{{cite web|first=Jan|last= Moir |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2187509/Our-musical-heritage-Oh-pull-Jan-Moirs-Olympic-Closing-Ceremony.html#ixzz24sWjCQHe |title=Our musical heritage? Oh, pull the other one |work=The Daily Mail |date=13 August 2012 |accessdate=30 August 2012}}</ref>

''[[New Zealand Herald|NZ Herald's]]'' Troy Rawhiti-Forbes wrote that there were "touches of brilliance, beauty, and bewilderment - often at the same time." However he called Russell Brand "tuneless", and during George Michael's performance he thought that "if there had been remote controls here in the stadium, people might have been reaching for them."  His "undisputed champions" of the night were the Spice Girls and The Who.<ref>{{cite web|first=Troy|last=Rawhiti<U+2013>Forbes|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/sport/news/article.cfm?c_id=4&objectid=10826622 |title=Olympics: Closing ceremony review |work=NZ Herald|date=13 August 2012 |accessdate=30 August 2012}}</ref>  David Rooney of the ''[[Hollywood Reporter]]'' noted that the show "had something for every generation" and was an "all-star...crowd-pleaser."  However he wonders whether non-British viewers would have understood references to ''The Italian Job'' and ''Only Fools and Horses''. Rooney concludes that the "Rio preview and the rousing Britpop marathon that preceded it were a reminder that the Olympics are as much about spectacle as sport."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/olympics-closing-ceremony-london-spice-girls-george-michael-361167 |title=Closing Ceremony of the London Olympics: Review |work=[[Hollywood Reporter]] |date=12 August 2012 |accessdate=30 August 2012|first=David|last=Rooney}}</ref>

[[Gary Barlow]] was called "inspirational, brave and a consummate professional" after performing despite losing his fourth child on 4 August.<ref>{{cite web|last=Furness |first=Hannah |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/london-2012/9471504/London-2012-Gary-Barlow-braves-personal-tragedy-to-perform-at-closing-ceremony.html |title=London 2012: Gary Barlow braves personal tragedy to perform at closing ceremony |work=The Daily Telegraph|date=13 August 2012 |accessdate=30 August 2012}}</ref> However, George Michael attracted some criticism for singing his new song "White Light" at the ceremony.<ref name="GB viewing">{{cite web|last=Hough |first=Andrew |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/news/9472327/Olympic-Closing-Ceremony-George-Michael-accused-of-promoting-new-single.html |title=Olympic Closing Ceremony: George Michael accused of promoting new single |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=13 August 2012 |accessdate=30 August 2012}}</ref> Critics saw this as shameless promotion.  Michael replied that it was his one chance to thank his supporters, which he didn't regret.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-19259865|date=14 August 2012|accessdate=21 August 2012|title=George Michael defends Olympics closing ceremony song|work=BBC News}}</ref> It was his first appearance since almost dying from pneumonia and "White Light" was about that experience.<ref name="controversial">{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/9473553/George-Michael-criticised-over-closing-ceremony-song.html|title=George Michael criticised over closing ceremony song|first=Anita|last=Singh|date=14 August 2012|accessdate=21 August 2012|work=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> Appearances by Russell Brand, Naomi Campbell and Kate Moss were also seen as controversial, as their previous behaviour had not always reflected Olympic ideals.<ref name="controversial"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2187447/London-2012-closing-ceremony-Twitter-backlash-appearance-Kate-Moss-Naomi-Campbell.html|title='Gold medal for phone throwing': Twitter backlash at appearance of Kate Moss and Naomi Campbell after Olympics Stadium was turned into a giant catwalk|first=Katherine|last=Faulkner|date=13 August 2012|accessdate=21 August 2012|work=The Daily Mail}}</ref>

As with the opening ceremony, United States broadcaster [[NBC]] was criticised for its coverage. John Clarke, writing for ''[[Forbes]]'', said it was wrong not to air performances from Ray Davies and Muse, as well as delaying the performance from The Who by an hour in order to broadcast the pilot of the sitcom ''[[Animal Practice]]'' followed by the late [[local news]].<ref>{{cite web|first=John |last=Clarke |url=http://www.forbes.com/sites/johnclarke/2012/08/13/is-nbcs-animal-practice-the-most-hated-show-on-television/ |title=Is NBC's 'Animal Practice' The Most Hated Show On Television? |publisher= |work=Forbes |date=13 August 2012 |accessdate=13 August 2012}}</ref> While in New Zealand, [[Prime (New Zealand)|Prime TV]] were also criticised for delayed coverage, running 20 minutes behind [[Sky Sport (New Zealand)|Sky Sport]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=10826600 |title=Complaints flow for Prime's closing coverage  |work=NZ Herald |date= |accessdate=30 August 2012}}</ref>

